  "prompt": "Is the correct term, \"I used to be\" or \"I use to be\"?",
  "response": "The correct phrase depends on the context in which you're using it. Here's a breakdown to help clarify:\n\n### **Affirmative Statements**\n- **Use \"used to.\"**\n  \n  When stating something that was true in the past but isn't anymore, you should use \"used to.\"\n\n  **Examples:**\n  - *\"I used to be a teacher.\"*\n  - *\"She used to live in New York.\"*\n  - *\"They used to go hiking every weekend.\"*\n\n### **Negative Statements and Questions**\n- **Use \"use to.\"**\n  \n  In negative sentences and questions, \"use to\" is appropriate. This typically happens because \"used to\" follows forms like \"didn't\" or \"did,\" which already contain the past tense.\n\n  **Examples:**\n  - **Negative:**\n    - *\"I didn't use to like broccoli.\"*\n    - *\"He didn't use to work here.\"*\n  - **Questions:**\n    - *\"Did you use to play the piano?\"*\n    - *\"Did they use to visit every summer?\"*\n\n### **Why the Difference?**\n\n- **Affirmative:** \"Used to\" functions as the past tense form of \"use to\" when indicating a habitual action or state in the past.\n  \n- **Negative & Questions:** The auxiliary verbs \"didn't\" and \"did\" already indicate the past tense, so \"use to\" remains in its base form.\n\n### **Quick Reference:**\n- **Affirmative:** I **used to** be\u2026\n- **Negative:** I didn't **use to** be\u2026\n- **Question:** Did you **use to** be\u2026\n\n### **Additional Examples:**\n\n- **Affirmative:** *\"She used to travel frequently for her job.\"*\n- **Negative:** *\"They didn't use to enjoy coffee.\"*\n- **Question:** *\"Did he use to live downtown?\"*\n\n### **Summary**\n\n- Use **\"used to\"** for affirmative statements about the past.\n- Use **\"use to\"** in negatives and questions because the past tense is already indicated by \"did\" or \"didn't.\"\n\nBy following these guidelines, you can ensure that you're using the correct form based on the structure of your sentence.",
